Fun with fonts

The default fonts in R might not be that interesting to you. Here is how you can get a little more flexibility.

Required packages

These example uses the following packages:

library(tidyverse)
library(extrafont)
library(extrafontdb)
library(ggspatial)

Loading some sample data

Lets start with this nice map I created that shows bus stop and trails in San Luis Opispo. It includes some text annotation as well.

slo_map

There are a few different text elements on this map. There are the axis labels, the text in the legend, the plot title, and the map annotation. The default font is Arial, and its fine. But maybe you want more options.

To make all the fonts on your computer available to R, type font_import() into your console and press Enter. You should only need to ever do this once. It takes some time to import all the fonts, so youll get a prompt to type y or n (yes or no) to confirm that you really want to do that. Type y and press Enter.

If you are seeing a lot of messages that say No FontName. Skipping., try typing remotes::install_version("Rttf2pt1", version = "1.3.8") into your console, then try again (a newer version of one of the packages extrafonts depends on seems to be a little broken, so this takes it back to an old one).

Now you can use the fonts() function to see a list of all the fonts that are available to you. Heres what I have on my computer (its a PC).

Now I need to load these fonts using the function loadfonts(). If you are working on a Mac, you can leave leave the parentheses empty (i.e.delete device = "win")

loadfonts(device = "win")

Setting the font for an entire plot

I can set the font for all the text in the font by setting text = in the theme() function.

slo_map +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "Garamond"))

Setting the font for individual elements

Maybe you want to use different fonts for different text elements. No problem.

slo_map +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(family = "Copperplate Gothic Bold",
                             size = 20),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(family = "Copperplate Gothic Light"),
        axis.text = element_text(family = "Calibri" ),
        legend.title = element_text(family = "Calibri", face = "bold"),
        legend.text = element_text(family = "Calibri" ))

Setting the font for annotation

There are some map annotation elements like north arrows, scale bars, and text annotation where you would set the font separately from the theme.

slo_map +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(family = "Copperplate Gothic Bold",
                             size = 20),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(family = "Copperplate Gothic Light"),
        axis.text = element_text(family = "Calibri" ),
        legend.title = element_text(family = "Calibri", face = "bold"),
        legend.text = element_text(family = "Calibri" )) +
  annotate(geom = "text",
           x = -120.73,
           y = 35.36,
           hjust = 0,
           vjust = 1,
           family = "Comic Sans MS",
           size = 3,
           label = "This map shows that the areas\nof San Luis Obispo served by\ntrails are distinct from (and \nminimally overlapping with) the\nareas served by transit. Few trails\nare easily accessible by transit.") +
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "tr",
                         style = north_arrow_nautical(text_family = "Copperplate Gothic Bold")) +
  annotation_scale(location = "br",
                   text_family = "Comic Sans MS")
